=== Lists

Lists are used to store a variable number of terms of the same type.

[source, morloc]
----
x :: [Int]
x = [1,2,3]
----

Lists do not yet have special accessors. List operations are performed through
sourced functions such as `at`, `slice`, `map`, `fold`, etc. You may import
many of these from the `root` modules.

The default `List` type should map to the "default" list in the concrete
language. In Python, this is `list`. In C++, it is `std::vector`. Now there are
certainly other ways to represent a list. In Python, you might want a more
efficient vector for representing fixed size boolean and integer types, such as
numpy vectors. There are also alternative data structures that are isomorphic to
lists (that can be represented as ordered sets of elements). These include
deques where values can be efficiently accessed and added at the beginnings and
ends of the container. We will discuss how to specialize the `List` type in the
Type Hierarchies section.

